{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccw3i5pWcsH5Ups8MSJP3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Bash `for`-loops come in a few flavors:\n\n**C-style (numeric):**\n```bash\nfor ((i = 0; i < 5; i++)); do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Range with a brace expansion:**\n```bash\nfor i in {1..5}; do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n\n# with a step (bash 4+): {start..end..step}\nfor i in {0..10..2}; do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Over a list of words / arguments:**\n```bash\nfor name in alice bob carol; do\n  echo \"$name\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Over array elements:**\n```bash\nfruits=(apple banana cherry)\nfor f in \"${fruits[@]}\"; do\n  echo \"$f\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Over files (globbing):**\n```bash\nfor file in *.txt; do\n  echo \"$file\"\ndone\n```\n\nA couple of tips: always quote `\"$var\"` to be safe with spaces, and use `seq` if you need a variable range, e.g. `for i in $(seq 1 \"$n\")`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5346,"cache_read_input_tokens":16998,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5346},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a44fc656-af71-4c28-9f8b-8bf2124f119f","uuid":"8e643809-fced-4e1d-adde-3a91ea25f323","request_id":"req_011Ccw3i4zQRQwWsfFpB9Xkq"}
